<body>
  <header>
    <h1>The Different Lights Used in Movie Setups</h1>
  </header>

  <main>
    <section>
      <p>
        Lighting plays a critical role in shaping the visual mood of a movie scene. Different lighting setups influence how we perceive characters, emotions, and environments. From high-key lighting in comedies to dramatic low-key lighting in thrillers, cinematographers use lighting as a storytelling tool.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common Types of Movie Lights</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Key Light:</strong> The main light source in a scene.</li>
        <li><strong>Fill Light:</strong> Used to fill shadows created by the key light.</li>
        <li><strong>Back Light (Rim Light):</strong> Helps separate the subject from the background.</li>
        <li><strong>Practical Lights:</strong> On-screen lights like lamps or candles used as part of the scene.</li>
        <li><strong>Ambient Light:</strong> Natural or existing light in the shooting environment.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Visual Example</h2>
      <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6e/3_point_lighting_setup.jpg" alt="Three Point Lighting Diagram" />
      <p>Three-point lighting is a standard technique in film and photography, combining key, fill, and back lights.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Learn More</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three-point_lighting" target="_blank">Three-Point Lighting on Wikipedia</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://nofilmschool.com/lighting-techniques" target="_blank">No Film School: Lighting Techniques</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

